<font color="#FF0000">VIETNAM WAR</font><br>
<tt>Mon Dec 23 15:45:49 US/Eastern 1996
</tt><p>
Why was this war the most horrific?  All war can be considered horrific if you happen to be one of the unluck people who has to bear witness to its destruction.  Among recent wars (20th century), Vietnam was the most horrific for America for the following reasons:<br><br>
1.  A lack of clear-cut goals or objectives from Day 1.  By not defining what we really intended to do, we did the same thing over and over again.  American soldiers fought over and over again for the same hills, valleys, towns, and rivers.  We took positions we never had intention of holding.  A good example-the taking of Hamburger Hill in May 1969.  The brave paratroopers of the 101st Airborne Division fought horrific battles for 11 days for a hill which was held for a short time after capture and then abandoned to the NVA.<br>
2.  The nature of the combat.  Vietnam was a war fought against a determined enemy who wanted us out at all costs.  There were no front lines in Vietnam.  Death could claim a soldier, whether he was sitting in a cafe in Saigon or way out in the &quot;Boonies&quot;.  For combat soldiers this produced a stress that was ever present.  My father was a combat engineer who spent most of his time working on construction projects in NVA controlled areas.  He said that he never really relaxed during anytime of his tour of duty.  Relaxation could be deadly for a soldier.  The war was mostly against an unseen enemy who started 7 out of 10 fire-fights.  The enemy usually picked when and where he intened to fight.  There were of course exceptions as we mastered the tactics of the enemy.  The enemy fought a war of boobytraps.  Amputations or crippling of the lower extremities were 300% greater then in WW II and 70% greater then in Korea.  Bobbytraps kill and maim without ever exposing the enemy.  Imagine how fustrating and cruel this is to our soldiers.  Combat in Vietnam has been likened to a nightmare that you couldn't escape unless you are killed or wounded.  Finally, Vietnam was not a guerilla war, it was a conventional war fought in tropical terrain.  This terrain <br>
aided the enemy in concealment. <br>
3.  Poor political performance-The government had no plan to win.  The believed they could fight a &quot;limited war&quot;.  There is no such thing.  They also were very slow to promote the necessary change to get us out.<br>
4.  Underestimation of the Enemy by our leaders (military and civil)  Our leaders underestimated the will of the Vietnamese people to edure and sacrifice.  We underestimated the enemy's skill and motivation.  The Vietnamese were willing to fight as long as necessary to drive us out.  Our presence gave them this determination.  The Vietnamese had previously fought the French and Japanese.  They knew that endurance and sacrifice would eventually pay off.<br>
5.  Lack of popular support - For the American soldiers, the war was fought without the support of many at home.  Many Americans were indifferent to the war.  This allowed the war to go on as long as it did.  Unlike veterans of past wars, America turned its back on its sons that fought there, when they returned home.  It seemes as though America blamed them, the soldier for the war.  They were not encouraged to speak about, they were discriminated against for jobs and schools and in some cases treated as radicals and losers by veterans of previous wars, such as WW II.<br>
The story of Vietnam must never be forgotten.  Our students need to be taught about Vietnam, so that this war is never repeated again anywhere else.  Finally, we need to listen and embrace the men and women that served in Vietnam.  They served in America's most horrible and longest war and each sacrificed a little of themselves for their country.
<p><code>--   (School teacher and historian) </code><p>


